The two open seats are part of the FOMC's Board of Governors. The are 7 Governors, appointed to 14 year terms by the President of the US. In addition to the 7 governors, there are also 5 Federal Reserve appointments to fill out the 12 member FOMC. It is common to see the governors positions left empty, as it increses the influence of the US banks, who are limited to 5 seats For example, currently there are 5 bank representatives and 5 Presidential appointed governors. Depending on whether Congress approves Presidential nominees, or leaves the positions open, is an indication of Congressional preference for a. banking or b. Presidential influence on the FOMC.

Trump has yet to officially nominate either Christopher Waller or Judy Shelton to the Board of Governors in spite of having tweeted his intentions to do so. Recent experience has shown that delays in formally putting the names to the Senate and starting the process is a fairly strong indication that these will not come to fruition, or that the names in question will withdraw rather than deal with a lengthy and/or contentious confirmation. Shelton is probably not a viable nomination. Waller, on the other hand, could make it through, although he would face a tough battle in maintaining his independence as a monetary policymaker in the face of Trump’s undisguised desire for a loyalist on the Board of Governors. https://whetstoneanalysis.com/2019/08/21/comment-dissents-in-the-fomc-vote-are-likely-to-continue-maybe-into-2020/

As @1MM1 pointed out, the average time to confirm nominees to be confirmed is 4.9 months. With the senate in recess for most of August, this confirmation timeless is way too tight.

They will confirm Christopher Waller first because he is an advocate of low interest rates which will appeal across party lines. Judy Shelton is a more challenging confirmation but I expect that a Republican led Senate will likely confirm both.

In general, I see Waller being confirmed and Shelton withdrawing her nomination because the Senate will not move her forward. Recent appointments can take 3 months to six months https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/trump-administration-appointee-tracker/database/?utm_term=.6bf86b8a5def But this is a tight 3-month window - actually, a two month window, given the Senate is in recess in August. If anyone could breeze through like he's 'with the band" - it's Waller b/c he already is "with the band" - he presently works at the St Louis Fed under James Bullard, and his views are well known, and he's fashionably dovish.

Shelton faces an uphill battle, while Waller is a more traditional candidate. Due to the controversy over Cain and Moore. It's possible they'll appoint Waller and pass on Shelton, or maybe do them both, but seems very unlikely Shelton will be appointed and Waller passed over.
